European debt restructuring is unavoidable.
Berkeley — it was just a Greek crisis, it was just a Greek and Irish crisis, people used to think that way, but that's not the case now, because it's clearly a crisis of the eurozone.
It is both easier and more difficult to deal with than one would normally suppose.
This crisis has a very simple economic logic.
Greece has fiscal problems.
Ireland's banking industry is problematic.
Portugal's private debt market is problematic.
Spain has problems in all three aspects.
Despite their differences, the conclusion is the same: all these countries have to go through the painful process of cutting expenses.
To offset the effects of a contractionary policy, the common approach is to combine domestic money-saving and devaluation of the currency.
Devaluation will enhance export competitiveness, which is to rely on foreign demand to supplement domestic demand.
However, these countries are all eurozone countries, they do not have an independent currency that can depreciate, so they can only use internal depreciation to replace external depreciation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve an effect of expanding domestic demand.
In fact, the resolve of these crisis countries to tighten their belts is no small one.
However, there is one economic variable that did not change with the adjustment of the other variables, namely the debt of the public and private sectors.
The government's accumulated debt in nominal terms has not changed, and neither has that of banks - except for some debts owed to junior creditors.
It is precisely this simple fact that gets the devaluation strategy into a self-contradictory situation: the more that wages and other costs are reduced, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes.
The heavier the debt burden, the more government will be forced to reduce public spending and increase taxes in order to meet its debt obligations, including those owed to the government's creditors, such as banks.
This in turn requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, thus creating a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a recession.
So, in order to make the internal devaluation strategy effective, it is necessary to find a way to lower the debt value.
Local government debt must be restructured.
Banks must convert debt into equity, and when banks cannot cover their debt, they should be dissolved.
The mortgage debt also needs to be written off.
Policy makers do not want to take this path, and that is understandable.
A contract is sacred.
The government is worried about losing confidence in the financial market.
If the creditors mainly come from abroad, especially foreign banks, setting off only hurts other countries.
These concerns cannot be said to be without reason, but it should not be concluded from them that it is unreasonable.
There are only two options: internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European heads of state must choose one of two.
They have ruled out the possibility of devaluation from outside.
However, internal devaluation must lead to debt restructuring.
Denying this point has neither reason nor logic.
The operation of debt restructuring is simple and clear.
The government can issue a batch of debt, the face value of which is discounted by a certain ratio compared to the existing debt value.
Bondholders can choose either to stick with their original bonds, exchanging them at face value, but with a later maturity date and a lower interest rate; or accept discounted bonds with a lower face value than their current bonds, but with an earlier maturity date and a higher interest rate.
This is not cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to succeed, there are three preconditions.
First, we must guarantee the safety of the new bonds for the bondholders.
Someone needs to come out to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when implementing the Brady Plan to restructure Latin American debt, it was the U.S. Treasury that played the role of "guarantor big brother".
Today, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, all countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, a country's reorganization will raise expectations of other countries and cause a spillover effect.
Finally, the banks that suffered losses due to debt restructuring must solidify their balance sheets.
These banks need to undergo real stress tests, not the kinds of scripted exercises they did earlier this year.
If debt restructuring implies capital insufficiency, a comprehensive debt to equity swap should be conducted for relevant banks.
If this is not enough, the government must step in to inject capital into the relevant banks.
This also requires unified action from all countries.
Once the bank's balance sheet is solidified, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debt without shaking the entire financial system.
Let's talk about the biggest difficulty now.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that the country's banks have a huge risk exposure in the debt of eurozone peripheral countries, the situation is critical.
They must convince the backbenchers and the electorate that using public funds as collateral for debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for a devaluation strategy; if Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it cannot shirk the responsibility of providing collateral.
In one sentence, European leaders, especially those in Germany, need to make the consequences sound more severe - otherwise, they'll face a disaster.
That's just the way it is.
